Julius Evola, while talking about a certain novelist, explains that many fail to see satisfactory results from their spiritual practices because they have a tendency to think with words and are unable to visualize and see figures, forms, images in their mind's eye

This is the exact same as Ray Peat explaining that an organism in a hypometabolic state with high levels of serotonin will always think in words, dream in words, be unable to imagine visuals (or even see them in dreams).

Low metabolism = Wordiness
High metabolism = Figure & Form
I like to point these out even if they start to seem repetitive because it's nice to show that biology and spiritual science fully overlap 1:1 when you understand both

Just found out there exists a "Pyramus and Thisbe Club" (the forbidden love couple that offed themselves) and it's not concerned with helping young people marry despite the wishes of families, but is composed of people really passionate about common parting walls between 2 houses

>The Club was formed to exchange news and opinions about interesting party wall cases

>The Club's motto, a quotation from the play, is "The wall is down that parted their fathers." The Club's quarterly newsletter is called Whispers.

>membership is drawn from mixture of surveyors, architects, engineers, other professionals and lawyers, all of whom have interest in party wall matters

>The Club continues to maintain relationships with Government and Parliament. Members of the Club have formed advisory panels

>The Pyramus and Thisbe Club has published a two volume "Collected Papers" from the first 20 years of its proceedings and "The Party Wall Act Explained" written by the members of the original working party, now in its second revised edition
